My observations after giving the data a prima facie glance:¶

  • The income column resembles boolean data
  • The fnlwgt column indicates the number of people the census believes the data point represents.
  • The education_num column indicates how many years a data point spent in education.
  • The capital_gain and capital_loss indicate the loss or gain incurred by a data point disposing of an asset.
  • The label in this dataset is income. This is a binary label of either <=50k or >50k

# Explore the data with visualizations
# I visualized all the data with vertical bar plots and histograms first, but realized this is not ideal
# I then visualized the data with vertical and horizontal plots and histograms. This makes the visualization easier to absorb

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define the columns for which I want to create vertical bar plots
vertical_bar_columns = ['relationship', 'race', 'sex', 'income']

# Define the columns for which I want to create horizontal bar plots
horizontal_bar_columns = ['workclass', 'education', 'marital_status', 'occupation', 'native_country']

# Define the columns for which I want to create histograms
histogram_columns = ['age', 'fnlwgt', 'education_num', 'capital_gain', 'capital_loss', 'hours_per_week']

# Loop through the columns for vertical bar plots
for column in vertical_bar_columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    order = df[column].value_counts().index  # Add this line
    ax = sns.countplot(x=column, data=df, order=order)
    
    total = len(df[column])

    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.3f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12)
    plt.title(f'Count plot for {column}', size=15)
    plt.show()

# Loop through the columns for horizontal bar plots
for column in horizontal_bar_columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    order = df[column].value_counts().index  # Add this line
    ax = sns.countplot(y=column, data=df, order=order)
    
    total = len(df[column])

    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.3f}%'.format(100 * p.get_width()/total)
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width()
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()/2
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12)
    plt.title(f'Count plot for {column}', size=15)
    plt.show()


# Loop through the columns for histograms
for col in histogram_columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    sns.histplot(df[col], kde=True, color = 'darkblue')

    # Calculate the statistics
    mean=df[col].mean()
    std_dev=df[col].std()
    var = df[col].var()
    quartiles = df[col].quantile([0.25,0.5,0.75]).values
    
    # Add vertical lines for mean, std_dev and quartiles
    plt.axvline(mean, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Mean: {mean:.2f}')
    plt.axvline(mean-std_dev, color='g', linestyle=':', label=f'Std. Dev.: {std_dev:.2f}')
    plt.axvline(mean+std_dev, color='g', linestyle=':')
    plt.axvline(quartiles[0], color='b', linestyle='-', label='25% Quartile')
    plt.axvline(quartiles[1], color='b', linestyle='-', label='50% Quartile')
    plt.axvline(quartiles[2], color='b', linestyle='-', label='75% Quartile')
    
    plt.legend()
    plt.title(f'Histogram of {col}')
    plt.show()

Task 2.2: Explore relationships between ten pairs of columns.¶

In [27]:
# I will define the pairs I want to work with the create for loops to handle the analysis.

# Define the pairs
pairs = [('race','income'),('sex','income'),('education_num','income'),('age','income'),('workclass','income'),('occupation','hours_per_week'),('education','hours_per_week'),('occupation','income'),('marital_status','income'),('relationship','income')]

# Loop through the pairs
for pair in pairs:
    # For two categorical variables
    if df[pair[0]].dtype == 'object' and df[pair[1]].dtype == 'object':
        # Use crosstab to get the count and percentage of each category
        crosstab = pd.crosstab(df[pair[0]], df[pair[1]], normalize='index')
        crosstab_count = pd.crosstab(df[pair[0]], df[pair[1]])
        
        # Perform a chi-square test
        chi2, p, dof, ex = stats.chi2_contingency(crosstab_count)
        print(f'Chi-square test between {pair[0]} and {pair[1]}:')
        print(f'Chi-square statistic = {chi2}, p-value = {p}')
        
        crosstab_percentage = crosstab.applymap(lambda x: "{0:.2f}%".format(100*x))
        crosstab_count = crosstab_count.applymap(lambda x: f"{x:,}")
        
        # Create a heatmap of the crosstab
        plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
        sns.heatmap(crosstab, annot=crosstab_percentage, fmt='', cmap='viridis')
        plt.title(f'Heatmap between {pair[0]} and {pair[1]}')
        plt.show()
        
    # For two numerical variables
    elif df[pair[0]].dtype != 'object' and df[pair[1]].dtype != 'object':
        # Use scatter plot and Pearson correlation
        plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
        plt.scatter(df[pair[0]], df[pair[1]])
        plt.title(f'Scatter plot between {pair[0]} and {pair[1]}')
        plt.xlabel(pair[0])
        plt.ylabel(pair[1])
        plt.show()
        corr, _ = stats.pearsonr(df[pair[0]], df[pair[1]])
        print(f'Pearson correlation between {pair[0]} and {pair[1]} = {corr}')
        
    # For categorical vs numerical
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
        if pair[0] in ['occupation', 'education']:
            sns.set_style("whitegrid")
            plt.xticks(rotation=45)
            plt.tick_params(labelsize=10)
        sns.violinplot(x=df[pair[0]], y=df[pair[1]])
        plt.title(f'Violin plot of {pair[1]} against {pair[0]}', size=15)
        plt.show()

Task 2.3: Posing One Meaningful Question and Seeking an Answer¶

I will be posing this question: Is there a significant difference in the number of hours per week worked by males vs females?

I have selected this because analysis of the relationships above do not give me a clear answer to explain what drives a person's income level.

The null hypothesis is that there is no difference in the number of hours worked per week by males and females

I will compute the mean hours worked by males and females, then visualize the distribution of hours per week for both groups and finally perform statistical tests to check if the difference is significant.

In [28]:
# I will strip the whitespace from the column labels
df['sex'] = df['sex'].str.strip()
# Set a theme from seaborn
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid") 

# Compute the mean hours per week for both males and females
mean_hours_males = df[df['sex'] == 'Male']['hours_per_week'].mean()

# Visualize the distribution of hours per week for both males and females
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))  
sns.histplot(df[df['sex'] == 'Male']['hours_per_week'], color='skyblue', label='Male', kde=True, binwidth=5)  
sns.histplot(df[df['sex'] == 'Female']['hours_per_week'], color='pink', label='Female', kde=True, binwidth=5)  
plt.title('Distribution of Hours per Week for Males and Females', fontsize=20)  
plt.xlabel('Hours per Week', fontsize=16)  
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=16)  
plt.legend(prop={'size': 15})  
plt.xticks(fontsize=14) 
plt.yticks(fontsize=14)  
plt.show()

# Perform a statistical test (t-test) to check if the difference is significant
male_hours = df[df['sex'] == 'Male']['hours_per_week']
female_hours = df[df['sex'] == 'Female']['hours_per_week']

t_stat, p_val = stats.ttest_ind(male_hours, female_hours)
print(f'T-statistic: {t_stat}')
print(f'P-value: {p_val}')

if p_val < 0.05:
    print('There is a significant difference in the number of hours per week worked by males and females.')
else:
    print('There is no significant difference in the number of hours per week worked by males and females.')

Task 3: Data Modelling¶

Task 3.1: Splitting the Data¶

I have chosen the Logistic Regression and Random Forest classification methods.

First I will encode the categorical and numerical variables, normalize the numerical variables and detect and handle outliers. Then I will split the data into three suites of test and training data sets. Then I will implement both the chosen models.

The aim of this is to create models that can predict whether or not a person will earn more and less than 50k a year

In [33]:
# Encode categorical variables
cat_columns = ['workclass', 'education', 'marital_status', 'occupation', 'relationship', 'race', 'sex', 'native_country', 'income']
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
label_mapping = {}  # To store the mapping of labels to original values

for col in cat_columns:
    df[col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df[col])
    label_mapping[col] = dict(zip(label_encoder.classes_, label_encoder.transform(label_encoder.classes_)))

# Normalize numerical variables
numerical_columns = ['age', 'fnlwgt', 'education_num', 'capital_gain', 'capital_loss', 'hours_per_week']
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
df[numerical_columns] = scaler.fit_transform(df[numerical_columns])

# Detect and handle outliers
outlier_columns = ['age', 'fnlwgt', 'education_num', 'capital_gain', 'capital_loss', 'hours_per_week']
for col in outlier_columns:
    q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower_bound = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
    upper_bound = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
    df = df[(df[col] >= lower_bound) & (df[col] <= upper_bound)]
    
suite1_X_train, suite1_X_test, suite1_y_train, suite1_y_test = train_test_split(df.drop('income', axis=1), df['income'], test_size=0.5, random_state=42)
suite2_X_train, suite2_X_test, suite2_y_train, suite2_y_test = train_test_split(df.drop('income', axis=1), df['income'], test_size=0.4, random_state=42)
suite3_X_train, suite3_X_test, suite3_y_train, suite3_y_test = train_test_split(df.drop('income', axis=1), df['income'], test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Instantiate the models
model1 = LogisticRegression()
model2 = DecisionTreeClassifier()
